        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-06-07T23:08:15.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"7\" data-topic=\"161638\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Interesting, the '17 was rather rich and I felt quite ripe, yet Dale mentions a slightly under ripe blackberry note in the '18.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I couldn\u2019t speak as to this particular wine, but many 2017 CdN reds were chaptalized\u2014which, combined with below average acidities, certainly contributes to their up-front fleshy charm and texture. In 2018, natural alcohols were almost universally quite a bit higher. Given the nature of Burgundy, there must surely be some 2017 which is an exception to the rule and attained higher natural degrees than its 2018 counterpart, but I certainly didn\u2019t hear of it yet! White Burgundy, given the yields, is another story.</p>",
